   <abstract >The nineteenth-century "moral reform" melodrama joined reform newsletters to warn audiences about social evil. These melodramas necessarily depicted vices like drunkenness, slavery, vanity, and rage. In Spectacles of Reform, Amy Hughes shows that the portrayal of such vices became spectacle for some of the nineteenth-century theatre. However, while the theatre depicted many types of vice and moral crusades, one vice seldom appeared. Sex work commonly appeared in reformist short stories and novels but rarely on stage. In a form that thrived on spectacle, danger, and the purity of women who needed saving, why did the perils of the "fallen woman" appear so infrequently? In addition to the question about sex work, this dissertation explores the questions: How were women and virtue presented on the Boston stage? How did the reality of life for middle-class women compare with the ideal presented on stage? What was the reality of sex work compared to the staging? Did melodramatic representations of women and sex on the Boston stage align with more conservative or more reformist social pressures? Ultimately, this dissertation connects attitudes about sex work and virtue in antebellum Boston to its portrayal on stage and link antebellum melodrama and the prostitution plays of the Progressive Era. Using a feminist and sex positive lens and employing literary analysis and cultural history this dissertation investigates gender and the value of women in the antebellum United States.</abstract>
